<p class="space-1">1965-2008</p>

<ul style="padding-bottom:1em;">
	<li>The three repositories, in various forms, arranged for the diary’s conservation. The conservation work included flattening out some of the diary’s leaves and, in some cases, laminating them. Stirling University carried out the conservation work on the David Livingstone Centre pages between March 1986 and May 1987.</li>
</ul>

<p class="space-1">2009-2017</p>

<ul style="padding-bottom:1.5em;">
	<li>In 2009, the David Livingstone Centre’s archivist Anne Martin rediscovered the Centre’s segments of the 1870 Field Diary while following up on a research query from Adrian S. Wisnicki.</li>
	<li>In 2010, the Livingstone Spectral Imaging Project arranged for further conservation of the David Livingstone Centre leaves of the diary (particularly so that the most fragile bits could be stabilized), then spectrally imaged all of the diary except for the four pages held by the British Library. These spectral images form the basis of the present critical edition.</li>
</ul>

<p>The present critical edition (2017), therefore, represents the last step in this historical sequence. The edition adds one final repository to the list, <em>Livingstone Online</em>, and brings together all the surviving the pages of the diary for the first time in over a hundred years.</p>

