The undertext pages thus do not run in sequence, and there is a gap between the first undertext leaf and the next two. These features suggest that Livingstone first tore these leaves out of the book, then wrote his diary entries only after flipping over vertically (thus not reorienting) the leaves with pages 23/24 and 21/22 of the undertext.<a id="link8" name="link8"></a></p>

<p><a href="#TOP" title="Go to table of contents" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">▲</a><strong> Third sub-gathering (Livingstone 1870h).</strong> The majority of text for this sub-gathering appears on the recto of a single leaf, which has Baker’s map of Albert N’yanza (and no Livingstone writing other than one minor calculation) on the verso. Livingstone has divided the recto of this leaf into quadrants (apparently following the original folds of the map – see <a href="/spectral-imaging/diary-across-hands-space-and-time-2#link3">Original folds</a>), then placed a page in each quadrant. As laid out clockwise from the top left-hand quadrant, the pages are arranged as follows: XX, XVII, XVIII (upside-down), XIX (upside-down). Baker’s map, on the verso, is oriented the same way as pages XX and XVII.</p>

