<p>When discussing the population of Bambarre just prior to leaving – i.e., when his information should be most accurate due to his long sojourn in the village – he first states that “their cannibalism is doubtful” only to reverse himself a few pages later by indicating that the locals are “undoubtedly cannibals” (1871b:LXXXIII, LXXXVII).</p>

<p>In the 1870 Field Diary, Livingstone never resolves this contradiction or, alternatively, never manages to circumscribe it in terms that are comprehensible to him. Rather, the diary’s narrative framework summons up an alternative African epistemological system – even if only tacitly – that stands alongside of the British one in which Livingstone operates. Livingstone, in turn, leaves the people of Bambarre on this note and heads for Nyangwe, where he will turn to his remaining iron gall ink and a torn-up copy of <em>The Standard</em> to compose the 1871 Field Diary.</p>

