        'value' => '<h4><strong><span style="font-family:crimson text;">Current Staff</span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong><span style="font-family: crimson text;"><a href="#TOP" title="Go to table of contents"><span style="font-size:16px;"><span style="font-family: source sans pro;">Top</span></span> ⤴</a></span></h4>

<p style="line-height:110%"><a href="/sites/default/files/behind-the-scenes/livingstone-onlines-staff/liv_013563_0001-crop-article.jpg"><img alt="Adrian Wisnicki, 2014, by Craig Chandler. Copyright Craig Chandler / University Communications, UNL. Used by permission." class="media-image attr__typeof__foaf:Image img__fid__306 img__view_mode__media_original attr__format__media_original" data-popupalt-original-title="null" src="/sites/default/files/behind-the-scenes/livingstone-onlines-staff/liv_013563_0001-crop-article.jpg" title="Adrian Wisnicki, 2014, by Craig Chandler. Copyright Craig Chandler / University Communications, UNL. Used by permission." typeof="foaf:Image&quot;" width="716" /></a></p>

<p class="space-1"><strong>Adrian S. Wisnicki</strong> (University of Nebraska-Lincoln) - Director - <a href="mailto:awisnicki@yahoo.com">email</a> - <a href="https://twitter.com/AdrianWisnicki" target="_blank">Twitter</a></p>

<p class="space-1"><em>Member of Project Team:</em> 2009-present</p>

<p class="space-1">Adrian\'s research focuses on applying spectral imaging technology to literature, developing sustainable digital projects, documenting end-to-end digital project management, and exploring the impact of intercultural dynamics on Victorian literature. He has published a monograph (Routledge, 2008); articles in <em>Victorian Studies</em>, <em>Studies in Travel Writing</em>, <em>History in Africa</em>, <em>Journal of Colonialism and Colonial History</em>, <em>Scottish Geographical Journal</em>, and elsewhere; and a digital project aggregated by NINES (2012). He currently directs two major NEH-funded projects, LEAP: The <em>Livingstone Online </em>Enrichment and Access Project and the second phase of the <em>Livingstone Spectral Imaging Project</em>, and is also collaborating on critical editions of Livingstone\'s <em>Missionary Travels</em> and the surviving Livingstone letters in South Africa.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p style="line-height:110%"><a href="/sites/default/files/behind-the-scenes/livingstone-onlines-staff/liv_013610_0001-crop-article.jpg"><img alt="Megan Ward, 2014. Copyright Megan Ward. Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 3.0 Unported (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/)." class="media-image attr__typeof__foaf:Image img__fid__306 img__view_mode__media_original attr__format__media_original" data-popupalt-original-title="null" src="/sites/default/files/behind-the-scenes/livingstone-onlines-staff/liv_013610_0001-crop-article.jpg" title="Megan Ward, 2014. Copyright Megan Ward. Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 3.0 Unported (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/)." typeof="foaf:Image&quot;" width="716" /></a></p>

<p class="space-1"><strong>Megan Ward</strong> (Oregon State University) - Co-director - <a href="mailto:ward.megan.elizabeth@gmail.com">email</a></p>

<p class="space-1"><em>Member of Project Team:</em> 2013-present</p>

<p>Megan is Assistant Professor of English at Oregon State University, where she studies the relationships between literature, culture, and technology. Her work on these topics has appeared in journals such as <em>Studies in English Literature 1500-1900</em>, <em>Configurations</em>, and <em>Victorian Periodicals Review</em>, and she is completing a book manuscript, <em>Human Reproductions: Victorian Realist Character and Artificial Intelligence</em>. She brings to <em>Livingstone Online</em> an interest in the digital representation and discovery of material histories.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p style="line-height:110%"><a href="/sites/default/files/behind-the-scenes/livingstone-onlines-staff/liv_013604_0001-crop-article.jpg"><img alt="Anne Martin, 2014. Copyright Anne Martin. Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 3.0 Unported (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/)." class="media-image attr__typeof__foaf:Image img__fid__306 img__view_mode__media_original attr__format__media_original" data-popupalt-original-title="null" src="/sites/default/files/behind-the-scenes/livingstone-onlines-staff/liv_013604_0001-crop-article.jpg" title="Anne Martin, 2014. Copyright Anne Martin. Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 3.0 Unported (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/)." typeof="foaf:Image&quot;" width="716" /></a></p>

<p class="space-1"><strong>Anne Martin</strong> (David Livingstone Centre) - Associate Director</p>

<p class="space-1"><em>Member of Project Team:</em> 2015-present</p>

<p>Anne is former IT analyst who much to her delight found she had time in retirement to develop new interests, and chose to turn to anything with a historical flavour, ranging from interest in genealogy to doing an Open University degree in history. She also has a keen interest in the David Livingstone story, stemming from voluntary involvement at the David Livingstone Centre, Blantyre, where she helps to look after the Centre\'s museum collection, including the museum\'s considerable amount of archival material.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p style="line-height:110%"><a href="/sites/default/files/behind-the-scenes/livingstone-onlines-staff/liv_013607_0001-crop-article.jpg"><img alt="Heather Ball, 2014. Copyright Heather Ball. Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 3.0 Unported (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/)." class="media-image attr__typeof__foaf:Image img__fid__306 img__view_mode__media_original attr__format__media_original" data-popupalt-original-title="null" src="/sites/default/files/behind-the-scenes/livingstone-onlines-staff/liv_013607_0001-crop-article.jpg" title="Heather Ball, 2014. Copyright Heather Ball. Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 3.0 Unported (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/)." typeof="foaf:Image&quot;" width="716" /></a></p>

<p class="space-1"><strong>Heather Ball</strong> (Morgan Library and Museum) - Coordinating Associate Project Scholar, Development Manager, and Project Closer</p>

<p class="space-1"><em>Member of Project Team:</em> 2010-present</p>

<p>As well as her degree in Library Science and Archives, Heather has a degree in Medieval Studies. She is active in both communities, and has given papers and published original research on the digitization, use, and sustainability of medieval manuscripts.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p style="line-height:110%"><a href="/sites/default/files/behind-the-scenes/livingstone-onlines-staff/liv_013609_0001-crop-article.jpg"><img alt="Adrian Wisnicki, 2014, by Craig Chandler. Copyright Craig Chandler / University Communications, UNL. Used by permission." class="media-image attr__typeof__foaf:Image img__fid__306 img__view_mode__media_original attr__format__media_original" data-popupalt-original-title="null" src="/sites/default/files/behind-the-scenes/livingstone-onlines-staff/liv_013609_0001-crop-article.jpg" title="Adrian Wisnicki, 2014, by Craig Chandler. Copyright Craig Chandler / University Communications, UNL. Used by permission." typeof="foaf:Image&quot;" width="716" /></a></p>

<p class="space-1"><strong>Kate Simpson</strong> (Edinburgh Napier University) - Associate Project Scholar and UK Outreach Coordinator</p>

<p class="space-1"><em>Member of Project Team:</em> 2010-present</p>

<p>Kate is a researcher in the Centre for Literature and Writing at Edinburgh Napier University. Her research is on nineteenth-century European missionaries in India and Africa, British imperial adventure romance fiction, and the creation and curation of digital representations of nineteenth century cultural artefacts.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p style="line-height:110%"><a href="/sites/default/files/behind-the-scenes/livingstone-onlines-staff/liv_013869_0001-crop.jpg"><img alt="Justin Livingstone, 2016. Copyright Angela Aliff. Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 3.0 Unported (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/)." class="media-image attr__typeof__foaf:Image img__fid__306 img__view_mode__media_original attr__format__media_original" data-popupalt-original-title="null" src="/sites/default/files/behind-the-scenes/livingstone-onlines-staff/liv_013869_0001-crop.jpg" title="Justin Livingstone, 2016. Copyright Angela Aliff. Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 3.0 Unported (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/)." typeof="foaf:Image&quot;" width="65%" /></a></p>

<p class="space-1"><strong>Justin Livingstone</strong> (Queen\'s University Belfast) - Associate Project Scholar</p>

<p class="space-1"><em>Member of Project Team:</em> 2013-present</p>

<p>Justin is currently Research Fellow at Queen\'s University Belfast, having previously worked at the University of Glasgow and completed his Ph.D. at the University of Edinburgh. His interests are broadly in colonial and postcolonial literature, travel writing and the relationship between religion and imperialism. He has published articles on these topics in journals such as <em>Studies in Travel Writing</em>, <em>Victorian Literature and Culture</em>, <em>English in Africa</em>, and <em>Literature and Theology</em>. His first monograph, <em>Livingstone\'s \'Lives\': A Metabiography of a Victorian Icon</em> (2014) was published by Manchester UP. He is currently developing a critical edition of <em>Missionary Travels</em> for <em>Livingstone Online</em>.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p style="line-height:110%"><a href="/sites/default/files/behind-the-scenes/livingstone-onlines-staff/liv_013608_0001-article.jpg"><img alt="Jared McDonald, 2014. Copyright Jared McDonald. Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 3.0 Unported (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/)." class="media-image attr__typeof__foaf:Image img__fid__306 img__view_mode__media_original attr__format__media_original" data-popupalt-original-title="null" src="/sites/default/files/behind-the-scenes/livingstone-onlines-staff/liv_013608_0001-article.jpg" title="Jared McDonald, 2014. Copyright Jared McDonald. Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 3.0 Unported (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/)." typeof="foaf:Image&quot;" width="716" /></a></p>

<p class="space-1"><strong>Jared McDonald</strong> (University of the Free State) - Associate Project Scholar and Lead Contact for South African Research</p>

<p class="space-1"><em>Member of Project Team:</em> 2011-present</p>

<p>Jared McDonald is a lecturer in the Department of History at the University of the Free State’s Qwaqwa Campus. He recently completed his Ph.D. in History at SOAS, University of London. Jared specialises in Khoesan studies and the history of British colonialism in the early nineteenth century Cape Colony. His other research interests include: “childhood” and child labour; settler colonialism and genocide; and the work of the London Missionary Society in southern Africa. Jared is currently collaborating on the digitization of Livingstone’s surviving letters in South Africa.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p style="line-height:110%"><a href="/sites/default/files/behind-the-scenes/livingstone-onlines-staff/liv_013603_0001-article.jpg"><img alt="Angela Aliff, 2014. Copyright Angela Aliff. Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 3.0 Unported (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/)." class="media-image attr__typeof__foaf:Image img__fid__306 img__view_mode__media_original attr__format__media_original" src="/sites/default/files/behind-the-scenes/livingstone-onlines-staff/liv_013603_0001-article.jpg" typeof="foaf:Image&quot;" width="716" /></a></p>

<p class="space-1"><strong>Angela Aliff</strong> (Indiana University of Pennsylvania) - Research Assistant and Interface Designer</p>

<p class="space-1"><em>Member of Project Team:</em> 2013-present</p>

<p>Angela Aliff holds a PhD in literature and criticism from Indiana University of Pennsylvania. Her research interests include early modern women writers, feminist epistemology, and reformist exegetical practices.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p style="line-height:110%"><a href="/sites/default/files/behind-the-scenes/livingstone-onlines-staff/liv_013886_0001-article.jpg"><img alt="Ashanka Kumari, 2016. Copyright Ashanka Kumari. Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 3.0 Unported (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/)." class="media-image attr__typeof__foaf:Image img__fid__306 img__view_mode__media_original attr__format__media_original" data-popupalt-original-title="null" src="/sites/default/files/behind-the-scenes/livingstone-onlines-staff/liv_013886_0001-article.jpg" title="Ashanka Kumari, 2016. Copyright Ashanka Kumari. Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 3.0 Unported (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/)." typeof="foaf:Image&quot;" width="716" /></a></p>

<p class="space-1"><strong>Ashanka Kumari</strong> (University of Louisville) - Research Assistant</p>

<p class="space-1"><em>Member of Project Team:</em> 2013-present</p>

<p>Ashanka Kumari is a doctoral fellow in English, Rhetoric and Composition and writing teacher at the University of Louisville. Her research areas include multimodal composition and pedagogy, digital humanities, and the intersections among identity studies, popular culture, and social media. Her work has appeared in <em>The Journal of Popular Culture</em> and <em>Blake/An Illustrated Quarterly</em>. Along with her work on <em>Livingstone Online</em>, Ashanka also serves as the assistant director of the Thomas R. Watson Conference and editor of <em>Cardinal Compositions</em>, assistant editor of <em>Kairos: A Journal of Rhetoric, Technology, and Pedagogy</em>, and is a founding editor of <em>MASH: A Journal of Media, Arts, and Humanities</em>.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p style="line-height:110%"><a href="/sites/default/files/behind-the-scenes/livingstone-onlines-staff/liv_013671_0001-crop-article.jpg"><img alt="Samantha Fitch, 2015. Copyright Samantha Fitch. Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 3.0 Unported (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/)." class="media-image attr__typeof__foaf:Image img__fid__306 img__view_mode__media_original attr__format__media_original" data-popupalt-original-title="null" src="/sites/default/files/behind-the-scenes/livingstone-onlines-staff/liv_013671_0001-crop-article.jpg" title="Samantha Fitch, 2015. Copyright Samantha Fitch. Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 3.0 Unported (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/)." typeof="foaf:Image&quot;" width="716" /></a></p>

<p class="space-1"><strong>Samantha Fitch</strong> (Indiana University of Pennsylvania) - Research Assistant</p>

<p class="space-1"><em>Member of Project Team:</em> 2014-present</p>

<p>Samantha is working on her PhD in literature and criticism at Indiana University of Pennsylvania. Her dissertation focuses on gender, fashion and economics in Victorian literature.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p style="line-height:110%"><a href="/sites/default/files/behind-the-scenes/livingstone-onlines-staff/liv_013868_0001-crop.jpg"><img alt="Mary Borgo, 2016. Copyright Angela Aliff. Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 3.0 Unported (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/)." class="media-image attr__typeof__foaf:Image img__fid__306 img__view_mode__media_original attr__format__media_original" data-popupalt-original-title="null" src="/sites/default/files/behind-the-scenes/livingstone-onlines-staff/liv_013868_0001-crop.jpg" title="Mary Borgo, 2016. Copyright Angela Aliff. Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 3.0 Unported (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/)." typeof="foaf:Image&quot;" width="65%" /></a></p>

<p class="space-1"><strong>Mary Borgo</strong> (University of Indiana) - Research Assistant</p>

<p class="space-1"><em>Member of Project Team:</em> 2015-present</p>

<p>Mary Borgo is a Ph.D. candidate in British Literature at Indiana University. Her research interests include Victorian literature, theater, and pre-cinema technology. Her dissertation traces the global history of early screen culture by exploring how Livingstone and other missionaries used projection equipment.</p>

