<p>These practices help account for the unusual textual configuration of 1871f:CLXII. Livingstone, it seems, designated this page for a note and initially jotted down a few observations as well as a list of supplies needed in Zingifure ink. Later when he had filled the preceding pages with entries in iron gall ink, he returned to this page and wrote across the bottom portion of the page. Next, he turned the page 90 degrees clockwise and wrote additional entries in iron gall ink over the Zingifure note already at the center of the page. Finally, he crossed out the entire central section of the page using iron gall ink. As a result, iron gall and Zingifure ink cover 1871f:CLXII in almost equal proportions, the text contains both "note" and "journal" entries, and the resulting manuscript page presents the reader with no less than four textual layers: the text of <em>The Standard</em>, the note in Zingifure, the diary entries in iron gall, and the cancellation in iron gall.</p>

