<h4><strong><span style="font-family:crimson text;">Initial History</span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong><span style="font-family: crimson text;"><a href="#TOP" title="Go to table of contents"><span style="font-size:16px;"><span style="font-family: source sans pro;">Top</span></span> ⤴</a></span></h4>

<p><a href="#TOP" title="Go to table of contents" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">▲</a> <strong>Locating the Manuscript.</strong> [qtip: Adrian S. Wisnicki|Adrian S. Wisnicki (Indiana University of Pennsylvania). Director, lead scholar, and principal writer for the multispectral critical edition of Livingstone\'s 1871 Field Diary.] first took interest in the manuscript of Livingstone’s 1871 Field Diary while researching a book chapter on Victorian travel to Nyangwe, the village in which Livingstone wrote most of the diary. The Livingstone<em> Catalogue of Documents</em> (Clendennen and Cunningham 1979) placed the manuscript in the John Murray Archive in London, but further enquiries revealed that the <a href="http://www.nls.uk/" target="_blank">National Library of Scotland</a> (NLS), which now owns the <a href="http://digital.nls.uk/jma/" target="_blank">Murray Archive</a>, had only low-quality photocopies of the manuscript made in the 1970s.</p>

<p class="space-1" style="line-height: 110%;"><a href="/sites/default/files/spectral-imaging/project-history-1/liv_016067_0001.jpg"><img alt="The David Livingstone Centre, Blantyre, 2010. Courtesy of the David Livingstone Centre." class="media-image attr__typeof__foaf:Image img__fid__306 img__view_mode__media_original attr__format__media_original" data-popupalt-original-title="null" src="/sites/default/files/spectral-imaging/project-history-1/liv_016067_0001.jpg" title="The David Livingstone Centre, Blantyre, 2010." typeof="foaf:Image&quot;" width="716" /></a></p>

<p class="space1" style="line-height:110%"><a href="/sites/default/files/spectral-imaging/project-history-1/liv_016068_0001.jpg"><img alt="The National Library of Scotland, Edinburgh, 2010. Courtesy of the National Library of Scotland." class="media-image attr__typeof__foaf:Image img__fid__306 img__view_mode__media_original attr__format__media_original" data-popupalt-original-title="null" src="/sites/default/files/spectral-imaging/project-history-1/liv_016068_0001.jpg" title="The National Library of Scotland, Edinburgh, 2010. Courtesy of the National Library of Scotland." typeof="foaf:Image&quot;" width="716" /></a><br />
<span style="font-size:12px;">(Top)&nbsp;The David Livingstone Centre, Blantyre, 2010. <em>Courtesy of the David Livingstone Centre.</em> (Bottom) The National Library of Scotland, Edinburgh, 2010. <em>Courtesy of the National Library of Scotland.</em></span></p>

<p>The <em>Catalogue</em> also noted that the museum based at Livingstone’s childhood home in Blantyre, the <a href="http://www.nts.org.uk/Property/David-Livingstone-Centre/" target="_blank">Scottish National Memorial to David Livingstone</a> (also known as the <a href="http://www.nts.org.uk/Property/David-Livingstone-Centre/" target="_blank">David Livingstone Centre</a> [DLC]), had previously owned the manuscript. As a result, [qtip: Wisnicki|Adrian S. Wisnicki (Indiana University of Pennsylvania). Director, lead scholar, and principal writer for the multispectral critical edition of Livingstone\'s 1871 Field Diary.] next visited the DLC in June 2009 and – thanks to the efforts of [qtip:Anne Martin|Anne Martin (David Livingstone Centre). Institutional contact for the multispectral critical edition of Livingstone\'s 1871 Field Diary.], volunteer archivist at the DLC – located the second half of the manuscript, those pages held under DLC identifier 297b. The whereabouts of the remaining pages remained a mystery. Wisnicki also discovered that the manuscript was illegible, with only some 15% of Livingstone’s text being visible. Livingstone\'s improvised ink had faded, while the newsprint over which he had written remained prominent, thereby obscuring the handwritten text. Despite these issues, Wisnicki had a hunch that the text could be recovered.</p>

