<span style="font-size:12px;">Members of the Livingstone Spectral Imaging Project team (Michael B. Toth, Ken Boydston, Roger L. Easton, Jr., Adrian S. Wisnicki) after climbing Arthur\'s Seat in Edinburgh, 27 June 2010. <em>Copyright Livingstone Spectral Imaging Project team. <a href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/3.0/" target="_blank">Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 3.0 Unported</a>.</em> Having just moved five days ahead of schedule, the members of the project team were in a rather jubilant mood.</span></p>

<p>The team moved to additional DLC and NLS pages in the following days. By capturing these images, the team ultimately doubled its anticipated results and laid the groundwork for the next phase of the project, a multispectral critical edition of Livingstone\'s <a href="/spectral-imaging/livingstones-1870-field-diary">1870 Field Diary and select 1870-71 manuscripts</a>, at no added cost. In fact, the team ran so far ahead of schedule that they concluded the imaging sessions by spectrally imaging a number of sample manuscript folia at the request of the NLS. These included two folia from a Gaelic 1467 manuscript by Dubhghall Albanach mac mhic Cathail (file prefix MS. 72.1.1), a few letters from Lord Byron (MS. 43325, MS. 43327, and MS. 43408), and the entire text of Sir John Franklin’s 1821 Field Diary (MS. 42237).</p>

