<p>Throughout the diary, Livingstone records a wealth of cultural, geographical, and agricultural information, including notes on personal decoration and facial features, local crops and cultivation methods, and topographical features. He is even moved to the poetic, describing, for instance, a "Mbanga village embowered in trees Euphorbias and wild fig trees" (Livingstone 1866c:[60])</p>

<p>Field Diary IV appears to be the same kind of book as the previous three field diaries: side-bound, covered in green silk that has become ragged with time. It is mainly written in grey pencil, with a few additions or corrections in blue pencil or black ink. As in previous diaries, Livingstone writes from both sides of the book at once, so the final twelve pages are written upside-down in relation to the rest of the text.</p>

