<h4><strong>I. File Naming</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <span style="font-family: crimson text;"><a href="#TOP" title="Go to table of contents"><span style="font-size:16px;"><span style="font-family: source sans pro;">Top</span></span> ⤴</a></span></h4>

<p>The <span style="font-style: italic;">first segment</span> consists of the initials of the institution holding this portion of the diary followed by the institutional shelfmark, as in the following example, where "DLC" stands for the David Livingstone Centre and "297c" represents the shelfmark:</p>

<p class="rteindent1">DLC297c_105-130_002v_TEI.xml</p>

<p>The <em>second segment</em> indicates Livingstone’s own page number(s), if provided. Roman numerals have been changed to Arabic numerals to ease reading. For any portions of the diary where Livingstone does not provide page numbers, we have numbered the folia consecutively beginning with 001, with the same number being used for the recto and verso:</p>

<p class="rteindent1">NLS10703_001_036r_TEI.xml<br />
NLS10703_001_039v_TEI.xml<br />
NLS10703_002_037r_TEI.xml<br />
NLS10703_002_038v_TEI.xml</p>

<p>The <span style="font-style: italic;">third segment</span> indicates the institutional page number(s), if provided. In addition, this segment includes the letter "r" (recto) or "v" (verso). For any portions of the diary lacking institutional page numbers, we have numbered the folia consecutively beginning with 001, with the same number being used for the recto and verso:</p>

<p class="rteindent1">DLC1120b_001r_001r_TEI.xml<br />
DLC1120b_001v_001v_TEI.xml</p>

<p>The <span style="font-style: italic;">fourth segment</span> indicates that the given folio of the diary has been transcribed according to TEI P5 guidelines by the presence of the "TEI" acronym:</p>

<p class="rteindent1">DLC1120b_001_001r_TEI.xml</p>

<p>The <span style="font-style: italic;">extension</span> ".xml" on all the example file names above indicates that each is an XML document.</p>

