<p>Livingstone uses both "and" and "&amp;" to connect words and phrases, but he clearly prefers "and." He consistently misspells "receive" and "conceive" as "recieve" and "concieve," respectively. He is also less than punctilious in using an apostrophe with the possessive "s." On occasion, when noting the appearance of a new moon, he draws a crescent moon rather than write out the word "moon." Finally, when breaking up a word over two lines, Livingstone sometimes places a hyphen at the end of the first line, sometimes at the beginning of the second line, sometimes in both places, and sometimes does not use a hyphen at all.</p>

